  "local_port": 33932,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I have a flight to prague. But In between I have to change flight at Paris! How to do that?",
  "response": "Changing flights in Paris on your way to Prague can be a smooth experience if you prepare properly. Here's a step-by-step guide to help you navigate your connecting flight:\n\n### 1. **Understand Your Itinerary**\n- **Single Ticket vs. Separate Tickets:** \n  - **Single Ticket:** If both legs of your journey (to Paris and then to Prague) are booked under the same reservation or airline alliance, your luggage is typically checked through to your final destination, and the airport handles most of the transfer processes.\n  - **Separate Tickets:** If you have separate bookings, you may need to collect your luggage in Paris and check in again for your flight to Prague. This requires more time between flights to accommodate baggage collection and re-check-in.\n\n### 2. **Know Your Airports and Terminals**\n- **Paris Airports:**\n  - **Charles de Gaulle Airport (CDG):** The main international hub with multiple terminals.\n  - **Orly Airport (ORY):** Mainly serves domestic and European flights.\n- **Prague Airport (V\u00e1clav Havel Airport \u2013 PRG):** Ensure you know which airport you\u2019re flying into and out of in both Paris and Prague.\n- **Terminal Transfers:** If your connecting flights are in different terminals, plan extra time to move between them using airport shuttles, trains, or buses.\n\n### 3. **Check Visa and Entry Requirements**\n- **Schengen Area:** Both France and the Czech Republic are part of the Schengen Area. If you're arriving from outside the Schengen Zone, you'll go through immigration in Paris.\n- **Transit Visa:** Depending on your nationality, you might need a transit visa even if you\u2019re not leaving the airport. Check the French consulate requirements beforehand.\n\n### 4. **Manage Your Luggage**\n- **Checked Baggage:**\n  - **Single Ticket:** Usually checked through to Prague.\n  - **Separate Tickets:** Might need to collect and recheck. Verify with both airlines.\n- **Carry-On Luggage:** Keep essentials, important documents, and valuables in your carry-on in case your checked baggage is delayed.\n\n### 5. **Allow Sufficient Connection Time**\n- **Minimum Layover Time:** Aim for at least 2\u20133 hours between flights to handle possible delays, immigration, security checks, and terminal transfers.\n- **Long Layovers:** If you have a longer layover and wish to explore Paris, ensure you have the appropriate visas and enough time to return for your connecting flight.\n\n### 6. **Navigate Through the Airport**\n- **Follow Signage:** Paris airports have clear signs in multiple languages. Look for signs directing you to \"Connecting Flights\" or your next terminal.\n- **Use Airport Services:** Information desks, airline lounges, and airport maps can provide assistance if you\u2019re unsure where to go.\n\n### 7. **Stay Informed**\n- **Flight Updates:** Use your airline's app or airport monitors to stay updated on gate changes or delays.\n- **Boarding Announcements:** Pay attention to announcements related to your connecting flight.\n\n### 8. **Prepare for Security Checks**\n- **Another Security Screening:** You might need to go through security again, especially if switching terminals.\n- **Prohibited Items:** Ensure your carry-on complies with security regulations to avoid delays.\n\n### 9. **Health and Safety Considerations**\n- **COVID-19 Regulations:** Check current requirements for transit and entry into the Czech Republic, including testing, vaccination, or quarantine rules.\n- **Health Precautions:** Follow recommended health guidelines, such as wearing masks and using hand sanitizer.\n\n### 10. **Emergency Contacts and Documents**\n- **Keep Essentials Handy:** Have your passport, boarding passes, and any necessary visas accessible.\n- **Contact Information:** Keep your airline's contact details and any booking references readily available.\n\n### **Example Scenario:**\n1. **Arrival at CDG (Charles de Gaulle):**\n   - Disembark and follow the signs for international transfers.\n2. **Immigration and Customs:**\n   - If arriving from outside Schengen, go through passport control.\n3. **Baggage Claim (if needed):**\n   - Collect your luggage if on separate tickets, then proceed to baggage recheck for your flight to Prague.\n4. **Security Screening:**\n   - Go through security checks for your next departure.\n5. **Transfer to Departure Gate:**\n   - Locate your departure gate for Prague, considering possible terminal changes.\n6. **Boarding:**\n   - Arrive at the gate in time for boarding announcements.\n\n### **Additional Tips:**\n- **Language:** While English is widely spoken, knowing basic French phrases can be helpful.\n- **Currency:** Have some Euros on hand for any incidental expenses during your layover.\n- **Stay Calm:** Airports can be busy and overwhelming, but keeping a positive attitude will help you navigate smoothly.\n\nBy following these steps and preparing in advance, you can ensure a hassle-free connection in Paris en route to Prague. Safe travels!",
